node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Ireland on September 15, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and castle.

node.text:
County Limerick – where the mighty River Shannon meets the Wild Atlantic Way! 💚

Not to be missed in Limerick city is King John's Castle, which has been standing tall on King's Island by the fast-flowing Shannon for over 1,000 years. Then you have the beauty of St Mary's Cathedral, which was founded in 1168. The historic streets here hum with activity. Why not pick up some artisan food at the famous Milk Market? Then pop into Treaty City Brewery for a local beer! 🏰🍺

Away from the buzzing city centre, the magnificent Adare Manor is one of the most luxurious stays on the island of Ireland, while the gorgeous village of Adare with its traditional thatched cottages makes for a delightful day out. 🏡😊

node.text:
The historic round tower and high cross of Monasterboice in Louth!

Just a one-hour drive north of Dublin, this fascinating monastic site dates back to the late 5th century. Founded by Saint Buite, the settlement was captured by invading Vikings in 968, but it was later taken back by Donal, the Irish High King of Tara. 👑⚔️

The imposing round tower stands 35 metres tall and the 5.5 metre Muiredach's High Cross is considered the finest high cross on the island of Ireland. ☘️

Thanks to @anna_travel_ireland_earth for the great photo.

node.text:
The Fermanagh Lakelands are a water-lover's paradise. ⛵😍

County Fermanagh makes up for its lack of coastline with a glistening array of lakes, rivers and waterways! From the early Christian monastery on Devenish Island to the ancient stone figures on Boa Island – which were carved by the Celts – this picturesque region is steeped in history.

Canoeing, water skiing, kayaking and wakeboarding are all popular activities on the water. And there are boat tours and water taxis available to help you explore far and wide.

Like what you hear? Then maybe it's time to hop aboard and set sail for this water wonderland 🌊🤩🛥️

node.text:
The sun has been setting on the Knowth Passage Tombs in Meath for over 5,000 years 🤯

The Great Mound is surrounded by 18 smaller satellite mounds. Knowth and the other megalithic sites of the Boyne Valley are a UNESCO World Heritage Site. A top sight to see in #IrelandsAncientEast 💫

Thanks to @mark_mcguire__ for the fantastic capture.
